I0331 11:44:05.295668   18955 client.go:683] GenerateStreamingChat request: {"enablePromptEnhancement":true,"history":[{"author":"USER","content":"can you continue to set up Render for me . i had to refresh the page and lost what i was doing"},{"author":"SYSTEM","content":"That is extremely frustrating! The good news is that because you are using a `render.yaml` file (also known as a Render Blueprint), you actually don't need to manually click through the Render dashboard to set everything back up. \n\nInfrastructure-as-Code files like this exist exactly for this reason—to save your configuration so you don't lose it!\n\nHowever, I did spot a small syntax error in your `render.yaml` file. In Render Blueprints, PostgreSQL databases need to be declared under their own `databases` array at the top level, rather than inside the `services` array with `type: psql`. \n\nHere is the fixed file:\n\n```diff\n--- /home/perrymckay1/render.yaml\n+++ /home/perrymckay1/render.yaml\n@@ -26,11 +26,4 @@\n           name: food-truck-redis\n           property: connectionString\n       # IMPORTANT: Add other secrets like SECRET_KEY in the Render dashboard.\n \n-  # -----------------\n-  # PostgreSQL Database\n-  # -----------------\n-  - type: psql\n-    name: food-truck-db\n-    plan: free\n-\n   # -----------------\n   # Redis Cache\n@@ -39,2 +32,8 @@\n     name: food-truck-redis\n     plan: free\n+\n+databases:\n+  # -----------------\n+  # PostgreSQL Database\n+  # -----------------\n+  - name: food-truck-db\n+    plan: free\n```\n\n### Next Steps to Deploy:\n\nInstead of manually creating your Web Service, Redis Cache, and Postgres DB one by one in the UI, follow these steps to deploy everything instantly:\n\n1. **Commit and Push:** Make sure this updated `render.yaml` file (and your `Dockerfile` since `runtime: docker` is specified) is committed and pushed to your GitHub repository.\n2. **Go to Render:** Log back into your Render Dashboard.\n3. **Create a Blueprint:** Click the **\"New +\"** button at the top right and select **Blueprint**.\n4. **Connect Repo:** Select the GitHub repository containing your app.\n5. **Deploy:** Render will automatically read the `render.yaml` file and spin up your Node app, PostgreSQL database, and Redis cache, perfectly linking their environment variables together!\n\nOnce the build finishes, all you will need to do is go to your newly created `food-truck-app` service on Render, click **Environment**, and add any sensitive secrets that aren't in your YAML file (like a `JWT_SECRET` or API keys for your automated emails). \n\n\u003c!--\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]How do I write a Dockerfile for this Node.js app?[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]How can I securely pass my JWT_SECRET to Render using the render.yaml file?[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n--\u003e","workspaceChange":{"files":[{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/render.yaml","language":"yaml","newText":"# This file configures the services for your application on Render.\n# Render will automatically detect this file and set up the environment.\n\nservices:\n  # -----------------\n  # Web Service (Your Node.js App)\n  # -----------------\n  - type: web\n    name: food-truck-app\n    runtime: docker\n    # The Dockerfile is in the root, so Render will find it automatically.\n    plan: free # Specifies the free instance type\n    envVars:\n      - key: NODE_ENV\n        value: production\n      - key: DATABASE_URL\n        fromDatabase:\n          name: food-truck-db\n          property: connectionString\n      - key: REDIS_URL\n        fromService:\n          type: redis\n          name: food-truck-redis\n          property: connectionString\n      # IMPORTANT: Add other secrets like SECRET_KEY in the Render dashboard.\n\n  # -----------------\n  # Redis Cache\n  # -----------------\n  - type: redis\n    name: food-truck-redis\n    plan: free\n\ndatabases:\n  # -----------------\n  # PostgreSQL Database\n  # -----------------\n  - name: food-truck-db\n    plan: free"}]}},{"author":"USER","content":"How can I securely pass my JWT_SECRET to Render using the render.yaml file?"},{"author":"SYSTEM","content":"\u003e Gemini 2.5 generated this response due to high traffic on Gemini 3\n\nThat's an excellent and crucial question! Storing secrets securely is one of the most important parts of deploying an application.\n\nYou should **never** put your `JWT_SECRET` directly into the `render.yaml` file. Because `render.yaml` is committed to your source control (like GitHub), adding a secret to it would expose it to anyone who has access to your repository.\n\nThe correct way to handle this is to use Render's built-in secret management. You can configure your `render.yaml` to expect an environment variable, but you will set the actual secret value in the Render dashboard.\n\n### 1. Update Your `render.yaml`\n\nModify your `render.yaml` to tell Render that the `JWT_SECRET` will be provided through the dashboard. You do this by adding the key and setting `sync: false`. This prevents Render from overwriting the value you set in the UI on subsequent deploys.\n\n```diff\n--- a/home/perrymckay1/render.yaml\n+++ b/home/perrymckay1/render.yaml\n@@ -23,7 +23,9 @@\n         fromService:\n           type: redis\n           name: food-truck-redis\n           property: connectionString\n-      # IMPORTANT: Add other secrets like SECRET_KEY in the Render dashboard.\n+      # IMPORTANT: Secrets like JWT_SECRET are added in the Render dashboard.\n+      - key: JWT_SECRET\n+        sync: false # This value is managed in the Render dashboard\n \n   # -----------------\n   # Redis Cache\n\n```\n\n### 2. Add the Secret in the Render Dashboard\n\nAfter you commit and push this change, your Blueprint will be updated. Now, you need to provide the actual secret value securely.\n\n1.  Go to your **Render Dashboard**.\n2.  Navigate to your `food-truck-app` service.\n3.  Click on the **Environment** tab in the service's navigation.\n4.  Under \"Environment Variables\", click **\"Add Environment Variable\"**.\n5.  Enter `JWT_SECRET` for the **Key** and paste your actual secret string into the **Value** field.\n6.  Click **\"Save Changes\"**.\n\nRender encrypts and stores this value securely. Your application will automatically restart with the new environment variable available as `process.env.JWT_SECRET`, without the secret ever touching your code repository.\n\n\u003c!--\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]How do I generate a strong, secure JWT_SECRET?[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]How do I use these environment variables in my Node.js code?[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n--\u003e","workspaceChange":{"files":[{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/render.yaml","language":"yaml","newText":"# This file configures the services for your application on Render.\n# Render will automatically detect this file and set up the environment.\n\nservices:\n  # -----------------\n  # Web Service (Your Node.js App)\n  # -----------------\n  - type: web\n    name: food-truck-app\n    runtime: docker\n    # The Dockerfile is in the root, so Render will find it automatically.\n    plan: free # Specifies the free instance type\n    envVars:\n      - key: NODE_ENV\n        value: production\n      - key: DATABASE_URL\n        fromDatabase:\n          name: food-truck-db\n          property: connectionString\n      - key: REDIS_URL\n        fromService:\n          type: redis\n          name: food-truck-redis\n          property: connectionString\n      # IMPORTANT: Secrets like JWT_SECRET are added in the Render dashboard.\n      - key: JWT_SECRET\n        sync: false # This value is managed in the Render dashboard\n\n  # -----------------\n  # Redis Cache\n  # -----------------\n  - type: redis\n    name: food-truck-redis\n    plan: free\n\ndatabases:\n  # -----------------\n  # PostgreSQL Database\n  # -----------------\n  - name: food-truck-db\n    plan: free"}]}},{"author":"USER","content":"How do I generate a strong, secure JWT_SECRET?"}],"ideContext":{"currentFile":{"codeLanguage":"yaml","filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/render.yaml","includedReason":"CURRENTLY_OPEN","segments":[{"content":"# This file configures the services for your application on Render.\n# Render will automatically detect this file and set up the environment.\n\nservices:\n  # -----------------\n  # Web Service (Your Node.js App)\n  # -----------------\n  - type: web\n    name: food-truck-app\n    runtime: docker\n    # The Dockerfile is in the root, so Render will find it automatically.\n    plan: free # Specifies the free instance type\n    envVars:\n      - key: NODE_ENV\n        value: production\n      - key: DATABASE_URL\n        fromDatabase:\n          name: food-truck-db\n          property: connectionString\n      - key: REDIS_URL\n        fromService:\n          type: redis\n          name: food-truck-redis\n          property: connectionString\n"},{"isSelected":true},{"content":"      # IMPORTANT: Secrets like JWT_SECRET are added in the Render dashboard.\n      - key: JWT_SECRET\n        sync: false # This value is managed in the Render dashboard\n\n  # -----------------\n  # Redis Cache\n  # -----------------\n  - type: redis\n    name: food-truck-redis\n    plan: free\n\ndatabases:\n  # -----------------\n  # PostgreSQL Database\n  # -----------------\n  - name: food-truck-db\n    plan: free"}]},"otherFiles":[{"codeLanguage":"dockerfile","filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/Dockerfile","includedReason":"CHAT_FILE_REFERENCED","segments":[{"content":"#\n# Stage 1: Build Stage\n# This stage installs all dependencies (including devDependencies) and runs the build script.\n#\nFROM node:18-alpine AS builder\n\nWORKDIR /usr/src/app\n\n# Copy package.json and package-lock.json to leverage Docker cache\nCOPY package.json package-lock.json* ./\n\n# Install all dependencies\nRUN npm ci\n\n# Copy the rest of your application's source code\nCOPY . .\n\n# Run the build script (e.g., for a React, Vue, or Angular frontend)\n# If your project doesn't have a build step, you can remove this line.\nRUN npm run build\n\n#\n# Stage 2: Production Stage\n# This stage creates the final, lean production image.\n#\nFROM node:18-alpine AS production\n\nWORKDIR /usr/src/app\n\n# Create and use a non-root user for better security\nRUN addgroup -S appgroup \u0026\u0026 adduser -S appuser -G appgroup\n\n# Copy package files and install *only* production dependencies\n# We'll do this as root, which is fine for a build step.\nCOPY package.json package-lock.json* ./\nRUN npm ci --omit=dev\n\n# Copy the built assets and necessary source code from the builder stage\nCOPY --from=builder /usr/src/app/dist ./dist\nCOPY --from=builder /usr/src/app/src ./src\n\n# Now, change ownership of all application files to the non-root user\nRUN chown -R appuser:appgroup /usr/src/app\n\n# Switch to the non-root user for execution\nUSER appuser\n\n# Expose the port your application will run on\nEXPOSE 3000\n\n# The command to start your application in production\nCMD [\"node\", \"src/index.js\"]"}]},{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/.codeoss/data/User/History/334840c1/zez0.js","includedReason":"RELATED_FILE","segments":[{"content":"const express = require('express');\nconst bcrypt = require('bcrypt');\nconst jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');\nconst pool = require('./db'); // Adjust path as necessary\n\nconst router = express.Router();\n\n/**\n * POST /api/auth/login\n * Authenticates a user, generates tokens, and saves the refresh token to the database.\n */\nrouter.post('/login', async (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const { email, password } = req.body;\n\n    if (!email || !password) {\n        return res.status(400).json({ message: 'Email and password are required.' });\n    }\n\n    try {\n        // 1. Find the user in the database\n        const userQuery = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1', [email]);\n        const user = userQuery.rows[0];\n\n        if (!user) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 2. Verify the password\n        const validPassword = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password);\n        if (!validPassword) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 3. Generate a short-lived Access Token (e.g., 15 minutes)\n        const accessToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id, roles: user.roles }, \n            process.env.JWT_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '15m' }\n        );\n\n        // 4. Generate a long-lived Refresh Token (e.g., 7 days)\n        const refreshToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id }, \n            process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '7d' }\n        );\n\n        // 5. CRITICAL STEP: Save the refresh token to the database for this user.\n        // This establishes the initial token that the /refresh route will check against.\n        await pool.query(\n            'UPDATE users SET refresh_token = $1 WHERE id = $2',\n            [refreshToken, user.id]\n        );\n\n        // 6. Define secure cookie options\n        const cookieOptions = {\n            httpOnly: true,\n            secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',\n            sameSite: 'strict',\n        };\n\n        // 7. Send the tokens in httpOnly cookies\n        res.cookie('token', accessToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000 }); // 15 mins\n        res.cookie('refreshToken', refreshToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000 }); // 7 days\n\n        // 8. Send a success response (do not send tokens in the JSON body)\n        res.status(200).json({\n            message: 'Logged in successfully.',\n            user: { id: user.id, email: user.email, roles: user.roles }\n        });\n\n    } catch (error) {\n        console.error('Login Error:', error);\n        res.status(500).json({ message: 'Internal server error during login.' });\n    }\n});\n\nmodule.exports = router;"}]},{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/.codeoss/data/User/History/334840c1/CyIa.js","includedReason":"RELATED_FILE","segments":[{"content":"const express = require('express');\nconst bcrypt = require('bcrypt');\nconst jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');\nconst pool = require('./db');\nconst { authLimiter } = require('./middleware/rateLimiter');\nconst { validateCsrf } = require('./csrf');\n\nconst router = express.Router();\n\n/**\n * POST /api/auth/login\n * Authenticates a user, generates tokens, and saves the refresh token to the database.\n */\nrouter.post('/login', authLimiter, validateCsrf, async (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const { email, password } = req.body;\n\n    if (!email || !password) {\n        return res.status(400).json({ message: 'Email and password are required.' });\n    }\n\n    try {\n        // 1. Find the user in the database\n        const userQuery = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1', [email]);\n        const user = userQuery.rows[0];\n\n        if (!user) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 2. Verify the password\n        const validPassword = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password);\n        if (!validPassword) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 3. Generate a short-lived Access Token (e.g., 15 minutes)\n        const accessToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id, roles: user.roles }, \n            process.env.JWT_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '15m' }\n        );\n\n        // 4. Generate a long-lived Refresh Token (e.g., 7 days)\n        const refreshToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id }, \n            process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '7d' }\n        );\n\n        // 5. CRITICAL STEP: Save the refresh token to the database for this user.\n        // This establishes the initial token that the /refresh route will check against.\n        await pool.query(\n            'UPDATE users SET refresh_token = $1 WHERE id = $2',\n            [refreshToken, user.id]\n        );\n\n        // 6. Define secure cookie options\n        const cookieOptions = {\n            httpOnly: true,\n            secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',\n            sameSite: 'strict',\n        };\n\n        // 7. Send the tokens in httpOnly cookies\n        res.cookie('token', accessToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000 }); // 15 mins\n        res.cookie('refreshToken', refreshToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000 }); // 7 days\n\n        // 8. Send a success response (do not send tokens in the JSON body)\n        res.status(200).json({\n            message: 'Logged in successfully.',\n            user: { id: user.id, email: user.email, roles: user.roles }\n        });\n\n    } catch (error) {\n        console.error('Login Error:', error);\n        res.status(500).json({ message: 'Internal server error during login.' });\n    }\n});\n\nmodule.exports = router;"}]},{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/.codeoss/data/User/History/334840c1/9PZd.js","includedReason":"RELATED_FILE","segments":[{"content":"const express = require('express');\nconst bcrypt = require('bcrypt');\nconst jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');\nconst pool = require('./db');\nconst { authLimiter } = require('./rateLimiter');\n\nconst router = express.Router();\n\n/**\n * POST /api/auth/login\n * Authenticates a user, generates tokens, and saves the refresh token to the database.\n */\nrouter.post('/login', authLimiter, async (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const { email, password } = req.body;\n\n    if (!email || !password) {\n        return res.status(400).json({ message: 'Email and password are required.' });\n    }\n\n    try {\n        // 1. Find the user in the database\n        const userQuery = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1', [email]);\n        const user = userQuery.rows[0];\n\n        if (!user) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 2. Verify the password\n        const validPassword = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password);\n        if (!validPassword) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 3. Generate a short-lived Access Token (e.g., 15 minutes)\n        const accessToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id, roles: user.roles, tokenVersion: user.token_version || 0 }, \n            process.env.JWT_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '15m' }\n        );\n\n        // 4. Generate a long-lived Refresh Token (e.g., 7 days)\n        const refreshToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id }, \n            process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '7d' }\n        );\n\n        // 5. CRITICAL STEP: Save the refresh token to the database for this user.\n        // This establishes the initial token that the /refresh route will check against.\n        await pool.query(\n            'UPDATE users SET refresh_token = $1 WHERE id = $2',\n            [refreshToken, user.id]\n        );\n\n        // 6. Define secure cookie options\n        const cookieOptions = {\n            httpOnly: true,\n            secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',\n            sameSite: 'strict',\n        };\n\n        // 7. Send the tokens in httpOnly cookies\n        res.cookie('token', accessToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000 }); // 15 mins\n        res.cookie('refreshToken', refreshToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000 }); // 7 days\n\n        // 8. Send a success response (do not send tokens in the JSON body)\n        res.status(200).json({\n            message: 'Logged in successfully.',\n            user: { id: user.id, email: user.email, roles: user.roles }\n        });\n\n    } catch (error) {\n        console.error('Login Error:', error);\n        res.status(500).json({ message: 'Internal server error during login.' });\n    }\n});\n\nmodule.exports = router;"}]},{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/.codeoss/data/User/History/334840c1/s6OL.js","includedReason":"RELATED_FILE","segments":[{"content":"const express = require('express');\nconst bcrypt = require('bcrypt');\nconst jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');\nconst pool = require('./db');\nconst { authLimiter } = require('./middleware/rateLimiter');\n\nconst router = express.Router();\n\n/**\n * POST /api/auth/login\n * Authenticates a user, generates tokens, and saves the refresh token to the database.\n */\nrouter.post('/login', authLimiter, async (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const { email, password } = req.body;\n\n    if (!email || !password) {\n        return res.status(400).json({ message: 'Email and password are required.' });\n    }\n\n    try {\n        // 1. Find the user in the database\n        const userQuery = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1', [email]);\n        const user = userQuery.rows[0];\n\n        if (!user) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 2. Verify the password\n        const validPassword = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password);\n        if (!validPassword) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 3. Generate a short-lived Access Token (e.g., 15 minutes)\n        const accessToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id, roles: user.roles, tokenVersion: user.token_version || 0 }, \n            process.env.JWT_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '15m' }\n        );\n\n        // 4. Generate a long-lived Refresh Token (e.g., 7 days)\n        const refreshToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id }, \n            process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '7d' }\n        );\n\n        // 5. CRITICAL STEP: Save the refresh token to the database for this user.\n        // This establishes the initial token that the /refresh route will check against.\n        await pool.query(\n            'UPDATE users SET refresh_token = $1 WHERE id = $2',\n            [refreshToken, user.id]\n        );\n\n        // 6. Define secure cookie options\n        const cookieOptions = {\n            httpOnly: true,\n            secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',\n            sameSite: 'strict',\n        };\n\n        // 7. Send the tokens in httpOnly cookies\n        res.cookie('token', accessToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000 }); // 15 mins\n        res.cookie('refreshToken', refreshToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000 }); // 7 days\n\n        // 8. Send a success response (do not send tokens in the JSON body)\n        res.status(200).json({\n            message: 'Logged in successfully.',\n            user: { id: user.id, email: user.email, roles: user.roles }\n        });\n\n    } catch (error) {\n        console.error('Login Error:', error);\n        res.status(500).json({ message: 'Internal server error during login.' });\n    }\n});\n\nmodule.exports = router;"}]},{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/.codeoss/data/User/History/334840c1/PpAz.js","includedReason":"RELATED_FILE","segments":[{"content":"const express = require('express');\nconst bcrypt = require('bcrypt');\nconst jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');\nconst pool = require('../db'); // Assuming this file is in a 'routes' directory\nconst { authLimiter } = require('../middleware/rateLimiter');\n\nconst router = express.Router();\n\n/**\n * POST /api/auth/login\n * Authenticates a user, generates tokens, and saves the refresh token to the database.\n */\nrouter.post('/login', authLimiter, async (req, res) =\u003e {\n    const { email, password } = req.body;\n\n    if (!email || !password) {\n        return res.status(400).json({ message: 'Email and password are required.' });\n    }\n\n    try {\n        // 1. Find the user in the database\n        const userQuery = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1', [email]);\n        const user = userQuery.rows[0];\n\n        if (!user) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 2. Verify the password\n        const validPassword = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.password);\n        if (!validPassword) {\n            return res.status(401).json({ message: 'Invalid credentials.' });\n        }\n\n        // 3. Generate a short-lived Access Token (e.g., 15 minutes)\n        const accessToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id, roles: user.roles }, \n            process.env.JWT_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '15m' }\n        );\n\n        // 4. Generate a long-lived Refresh Token (e.g., 7 days)\n        const refreshToken = jwt.sign(\n            { id: user.id }, \n            process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET, \n            { expiresIn: '7d' }\n        );\n\n        // 5. CRITICAL STEP: Save the refresh token to the database for this user.\n        // This establishes the initial token that the /refresh route will check against.\n        await pool.query(\n            'UPDATE users SET refresh_token = $1 WHERE id = $2',\n            [refreshToken, user.id]\n        );\n\n        // 6. Define secure cookie options\n        const cookieOptions = {\n            httpOnly: true,\n            secure: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production',\n            sameSite: 'strict',\n        };\n\n        // 7. Send the tokens in httpOnly cookies\n        res.cookie('token', accessToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 15 * 60 * 1000 }); // 15 mins\n        res.cookie('refreshToken', refreshToken, { ...cookieOptions, maxAge: 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000 }); // 7 days\n\n        // 8. Send a success response (do not send tokens in the JSON body)\n        res.status(200).json({\n            message: 'Logged in successfully.',\n            user: { id: user.id, email: user.email, roles: user.roles }\n        });\n\n    } catch (error) {\n        console.error('Login Error:', error);\n        res.status(500).json({ message: 'Internal server error during login.' });\n    }\n});\n\nmodule.exports = router;"}]},{"filePath":"/home/perrymckay1/node_modules/@types/node/timers.d.ts","includedReason":"RELATED_FILE","segments":[{"content":"/**\n * The `timer` module exposes a global API for scheduling functions to\n * be called at some future period of time. Because the timer functions are\n * globals, there is no need to import `node:timers` to use the API.\n *\n * The timer functions within Node.js implement a similar API as the timers API\n * provided by Web Browsers but use a different internal implementation that is\n * built around the Node.js [Event Loop](https://nodejs.org/en/docs/guides/event-loop-timers-and-nexttick/#setimmediate-vs-settimeout).\n * @see [source](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/v25.x/lib/timers.js)\n */\ndeclare module \"node:timers\" {\n    import { Abortable } from \"node:events\";\n    import * as promises from \"node:timers/promises\";\n    export interface TimerOptions extends Abortable {\n        /**\n         * Set to `false` to indicate that the scheduled `Timeout`\n         * should not require the Node.js event loop to remain active.\n         * @default true\n         */\n        ref?: boolean | undefined;\n    }\n    global {\n        namespace NodeJS {\n            /**\n             * This object is created internally and is returned from `setImmediate()`. It\n             * can be passed to `clearImmediate()` in order to cancel the scheduled\n             * actions.\n             *\n             * By default, when an immediate is scheduled, the Node.js event loop will continue\n             * running as long as the immediate is active. The `Immediate` object returned by\n             * `setImmediate()` exports both `immediate.ref()` and `immediate.unref()`\n             * functions that can be used to control this default behavior.\n             */\n            interface Immediate extends RefCounted, Disposable {\n         